SIMPLE: trivial
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trivial
<hw>Triv"i*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>trivialis</ets>, properly, that is in, or belongs to, the
crossroads or public streets; hence, that may be found everywhere,
common, fr. <ets>trivium</ets> a place where three roads meet, a
crossroad, the public street; <ets>tri-</ets> (see <er>Tri-</er>) +
<ets>via</ets> a way: cf. F. <ets>trivial</ets>. See
<er>Voyage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Found anywhere; common.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Ordinary; commonplace; trifling; vulgar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As a scholar, meantime, he was <qex>trivial</qex>, and incapable
of labor.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of little worth or importance; inconsiderable;
trifling; petty; paltry; <as>as, a <ex>trivial</ex> subject or
affair</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>trivial</qex> round, the common task.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the trivium.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Trivial name</b></col> <fld>(Nat. Hist.)</fld>, <cd>the
specific name.</cd></cs><-- (b) <fld>(Chem.)</fld> The common name, not
describing the structure and from which the structure cannot be deduced;
-- contrasted with <contr>systematic name</contr>. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trivial</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trivial
<hw>Triv"i*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the three liberal arts
forming the trivium.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Skelton.
Wood.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trivialism</ent>⟦br⟧
